{"id":"1111.5216","submitter":"Ilya Ponomarenko","authors":"Sergei Evdokimov, Istv\\'an Kov\\'acs, Ilya Ponomarenko","title":"Characterization of cyclic Schur groups","comments":"the second version; the proof was substantially improved; 29 pages","journal-ref":"St. Petersburg Math. J. 25 (2014), no. 5, 755-773","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A finite group $G$ is called a Schur group, if any Schur ring over $G$ is the\ntransitivity module of a permutation group on the set $G$ containing the\nregular subgroup of all right translations. It was proved by R. P\\\"oschel\n(1974) that given a prime $p\\ge 5$ a $p$-group is Schur if and only if it is\ncyclic. We prove that a cyclic group of order $n$ is a Schur group if and only\nif $n$ belongs to one of the following five (partially overlapped) families of\nintegers: $p^k$, $pq^k$, $2pq^k$, $pqr$, $2pqr$ where $p,q,r$ are distinct\nprimes, and $k\\ge 0$ is an integer.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 22 Nov 2011 15:15:19 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sat, 8 Sep 2012 13:01:47 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-05-07"}
